PFEssay: I think my past self was a little more bitter than my current self.   My past self in particular didn't trust people, or feel close to many people.  I think looking back on your past self and being connected is that you can learn from your mistakes.  You can always look at yourself and think you are in a better, or worse place than you were in the past.  My past self was good at looking out for himself, but quite literally nothing else.  I now try to temper looking after myself, with helping others.

PREssay: Feeling connected helps you to remember who you are and what you have come from no matter where you go in life. It is good for me to act like my past self in times of success because it would remind me to remain humble in all that I do. I think that using my past self as a motivator for myself today would help because it reminds me of where I came from and how I want to do better. My past self is good at working hard and remaining humble in all that I do.

PFEssay: I mean I can understand the benefits of remembering actions and reactions that led to life lessons. That way you don't repeat the problem again. Change is good and healthy. Plus it's good to remember everything I never want to be again. It's the only reason that if I had to go back I wouldn't change a single thing. Cuz then I wouldn't know what I know.

I would motivate my self today by being really goofy or fun. I was really care free when I was younger and its an important thing to me.I still am like this but have more responsibility now so it is more difficult to be. I want to climb mountain and skydive. I want to go skateboard again. It would help to be more stress free. It would also help in making friends.

FFEssay: If we're lonely, for example, the message might show up as a stab in the heart, a tug in the stomach, a welling behind the eyes, or all three. Counterintuitive as it may seem, to feel a painful emotion fully, at the site of its delivery, is the best way to help it diminish. Not feeling the emotion, on the other hand, causes it to grow stronger, remain longer, and mess up our lives in many ways.  But emotions are inside of us, so we can't actually run away from them. All we can do, therefore, is attempt to stuff them down or numb ourselves to their affects.

FREssay: I wake up and go for a run. I enjoy exercising since it makes me feel better and helps me sleep better at night. I also eat the same thing for breakfast every day, toast with peanut butter and jam and orange juice. I go to work usually nearly everyday, sometimes I work from home. When I go to work I take the bus. It's convenient and better for the environment plus it's cheaper. I don't have to pay for parking or gas. I save about $40 a month since I take the bus to work. I can also do other things instead of worrying about driving. I spend my day at work and then I go home and spend time with my family. I love my family; my wife and kids. It's almost always a good time to spend time with them. Sometimes they have their moments, but all in all it's a pleasure being a husband and father. On the weekends I change up my routine a bit. I usually go for a longer run on Saturday mornings since I have more time. On Sundays I attend a lot of church meetings. I‰Ûªm part of the local congregation leadership team so I attend a lot of leadership meetings in the morning prior to our church services. It takes time, but it is very fulfilling. I enjoy working with others and taking time from my personal life to socialize with others. It feels good to interact with others throughout the day. Much better face-to-face than over e-mail, text and chat.

PREssay: My past self was very good at being confident. My past self didn't take shit from anyone, which was a good thing. She was self-assured and good at what she did. She demanded that she be treated with respect and she got it. She was very driven and admirable for that fact.

FFEssay: The benefits of feeling connected to your future are to help give you something to look forward to. It helps motivate you to work hard and try your best in the present. It is good to act like your future self during a time when you need to take on more responsibility. For example, getting married would be a good time to act like your future self. Me bringing on my future self would help me do my job, and act like a fair person to others.

PFEssay: I think the main benefit to feeling connected to your past is to learn from your past self and grow from your past self. I think it's an interesting and maybe important concept to also try to identify ways in which your past self was successful and a role model, and to emulate those. Looking at my past self, I believe I used to be more disciplined in my schoolwork. I had more drive to perform well in school, and I would probably do well to find that drive again. This is an interesting concept I had not considered before.

FFEssay: I believe everyone should envision themselves in the future and what they want. For me, I have worked tirelessly in order to get the things I wanted by age 25 (2 cars, and a house). By envisioning that future self and seeing how I would feel at that moment, it has given me the drive to work endlessly to make this dream become a reality. I don't believe there is a right time to start this process. Every day that you aren't thinking of that future is a wasted day.

I want to be like Donald Trump. I want to be a rich narcissist. I want to be the president. I want to rob from the poor and give to the rich. The ultra super rich. I want to blame the poor people and Mexicans and North Korea and steal everything from people that are not like me and support pedophiles and be a hypocrite.

The future is going to be a dark and rather bleak time, in my opinion. Mankind is not working to seriously tackle the problems of overpopulation, scarcity of resources or even global warming/climate change. Given that those three problems need to have solutions developed now and could potentially lead to human extinction, either separately or combined, this lack of serious effort is mind boggling.It's also very likely that nature is working on one or more types of biologically-based population controls that we will only find out about when they become a problem for us. When or if the human population hits a certain point, there are very good reasons to believe that a pandemic illness or even mass sterility will come to the fore to act as brakes on further growth.Finally, the rather bizarre push for artificial intelligence will probably create one or more intelligences that mankind will almost certainly not be able to control. Since these intelligences would be unburdened by emotion and any thoughts of loyalty it's conceivable that they could see that a solution to their problems would be the extinction of mankind and act accordingly.

I work at an Adult Family Home caring for individuals who need care 24 hours a day. They either can't live on their own or don't have a family who can devote time to them. They are all wonderful people and I really enjoy my position. I feel like part of their family. I currently work with seniors above the age of 65 who are relativity healthy.

FREssay: I feel like my future self is important because that's who I want to be. I am currently a photographer at a small company. I want to expand the company and grow as a photographer. I want to be more well-known and I want to get more business. I also want to become better at drawing (a major hobby of mine). I will be a much more creative person in the future and I will love what I do. I will also hopefully be making more money. I will be a much more self-confident person, as well.

PREssay: Work was a big motivator of my-past-self. If I could learn one lesson from my-past-self it would be the value of working hard. Having that motivation would be beneficial. The career has been a bit behind with the demands of home, family, sports and the like. I know that I could get more from the career if I would put a bit more effort into it. That's the my-past-self lesson of the day.

FREssay: My future self is definitely a role model. How I prepare today will matter greatly in the future.  First of all thinking about future health and wellness encourages me to eat a healthy diet and exercise.  I want to be healthy when I retire so that is important.  Secondly, I want to be financially secure.  That is why I have a strong 401K package.

My future self is more confident than my present self. My future self is also more competent than my present self. I am currently self-employed as a writer and I'm still trying to get everything figured out. Hopefully, my future self will actually have it all figured out. I suppose "acting like" my future self means pretending I have everything figured out, even though I don't. But it could be one of those self-fulfilling prophesy type of deals.

PFEssay: Was motivated to get up in the morning. Actively sought out new sexual and romantic partners. Had a damn job. Kept in touch with a wide network of people. Was confident enough not to care very much about other people's opinions. Took pride in being who I was. Wrote every day. Did experience a lot more stress, and was too irritible as a result. Had lots of interests. Always had more irons in the fire than I could keep track of.

FFEssay: I hope to start my own buissness.I hope to pay of my car. I hope to be sent free .I want to be propsperous. I want to be established. I want my child toice comfortable and I want my child to be a independent and a good student and I want the best for my family

PREssay: A benefit that I get when I feel connected to my past self is reassurance that I am going in the right direction and am making good progress in life. A good time for me to act like my past self is when I feel like I am facing something I can't handle and I need to give myself reassurance that I am going to make it through things. What motivates me about my past self is my open-mindedness that I had and how I was able to face anything head on. Situations such as asking my boss for a raise, buying a home for the first time, and dealing with a death of a close friend. My past self is good at dealing with the situation at hand and making the most out of it. My past self always looked towards the future, even though it might seem bleak.

My past self was a workaholic and very concerned about pleasing everyone. I am more confident now, but I do not think I try as hard as my past self. Acting like my past self would make me pay more attention to detail in my work, look for more opportunities to advance, and probably be more of a team player. While I don't want to revert to my past self, I could take a few pointers that would improve my work ethic and attitude. PREssay: Dear Past Me,First off, those red glasses that you thought were so cute when you were twelve? How could you do that to us? Red glasses, really? You couldn't have just gone with black? I know that you wanted to be unique, but we were stuck with those glasses for years. Honestly, I wonder if I should blame you, or our mom who let us walk out of the store with them.But at least you stuck to yourself. I'll give you props for that. It can be hard trying to stay true to yourself. At least in high school it is. We went through some pretty crazy phases, especially the weird hipster phase. Good thing that's over with.You don't have to look and act a certain way to impress people. I wish I could've learned that sooner. You didn't need to have hair feathers in middle school because everybody had them. If you liked them, then sure, but don't try lying to me. I know that you regretted getting them every time you brushed your hair.Speaking of middle school, honestly, don't even try. No matter how cute your clothes were or who your friends were or how you acted, you'll hate yourself. Everybody ends up hating their middle school self, it's just a given. Puberty, transitioning between elementary to middle school, and the fashion alone ... middle school selves are the worst. Now I'm not saying that I hated myself right after middle school. Of course not. It took years to realize that middle school was the most awkward time of our life and we sort of just want to forget about it.Past self, all of those things that we wanted to do but thought we were too old or it wasn't cool enough or nobody else wanted to do it with us? We should have just done it. Remember when you thought it'd be cool to be a cheerleader? You should've tried out, it could've been so much fun! And if it wasn't, you always could've quit rather than always wonder if you could've done it. Or at sixth-grade camp, you were so sure that you were afraid of heights that you didn't climb the rock wall, man do I wish you did.But there are some things that I really appreciate you doing for me. Choosing the IB program, for example, who knows who we'd be without those crazy two years? We definitely wouldn't be who we are now. Or figuring out that you wanted to be a writer and not a vet ... we'd be miserable in vet school.All and all, past self, I know that there will be times when I hate you (let me just bring up the whole red glasses situation again), but there will never be times when I regret you. Everything you did and didn't do made us into who we are today. And, honestly, in comparison to who we could have been, where we are today is amazing.

PREssay: My past self was a trusting and loving person.  I think it is good to be connected to my past because it recalls a time that I learned many good lessons.  For example, I learned that love is not selfish.  Love means caring for others, and looking out for them as I saw my great grandma do across 4 generations. I learned that people will treat you unfairly, but that you must forgive them and move on and not allow it to change who you are. People can become hardened to who they were by hardship in their lives.  It can be a good thing to cast aside your present feelings and practice who you use to be.

PFEssay: Thinking back to my past self, I can think of things I could learn from him. My past self was more optimistic than I am today. Recent times have made me more cynically, even about people I once had respect for. My past self was more open to trying new things. I could learn from this to my benefit today.

FREssay: This person is very caring and giving and makes me want to do more. HE is good for me since he always try to be a good person. HE is good at caring about others and giving. He wants to make the world a better place. He goes out of his way to help others and wants to continue to do so. He makes sure that everyone is always working their hardest.

PREssay: My past self made a plan to lose some weight.  I didn't have a lot of weight to lose, but I wanted to lose some.  So I made it a habit to eat correctly more often than not, and exercise often.  My past self has the discipline to do something everyday no matter how I was feeling. So in that regard, my past self could show me that I am capable of moving my body more often than I do now.  Once I lost the weight, I continued to keep up with my habit, it becoming my life, my thing.  My past self would see "motivational coaches" from companies selling product and use them as motivation that I could do it.  I could use my past self as that motivation now.   The only problem with my past self, is that the habit started to make me feel 'not healthy', it was too much.  I didn't have time for any other activities and it didn't feel like being this small small size was worth it.  So there are lessons I can take, and lessons I can leave.  My past self ate a little bit healthier, thinking all of the time in their head,  I can't have that, I can't have that, I'll have this.  I could borrow a little bit of that to start to make healthier choices more often than not again, to help make it a good and healthy habit, instead of a draining one.
